We create the tools, standards and protocols necessary for a decentralized geospatial web, simplifying how Web3 developers integrate spatial and location data into their apps.

questions.query: Impact statement - what real world problem do you solve and how
questions.explanation:
Astral provides Web3 builders with the tools they need to develop location-based dapps and work with geospatial data.

Limited tools and challenges intrinsic to working with spatial data means there are very few location-based apps in Web3. We're developing these primitives — our Location Proof Protocol, spatial data structures and algorithms for onchain GIS systems, and spatial registries built using these algorithms. We're also working to support the onchain geospatial community by co-chairing the Decentralized Geospatial Web Working Group with the EASIER Data Initiative, out of the University of Maryland.

By solving problems related to building with location data, we aim to help Web3 developers unlock a new vertical of dapps. We're particularly focused on social and environmental impact, though our tools are useful in social, gaming, mobility, DePIN, events and other use cases.

questions.query: Celo leverage - how does your project contributed to the Celo ecosystem?
questions.explanation:
Astral enhances the Celo ecosystem by providing our Location Proof Protocol to the Celo network. (Celo is the first mainnet we've deployed v0.1 of the location proof EAS schema!)

This deployment aligns closely with Celo's strategic focus on leveraging blockchain for social impact, specifically in climate action, real-world asset management, and decentralized physical infrastructures (DePIN).

Prior work includes the creation of GeoNFTs with Kolektivo — tokenized land parcels linked with environmental state monitoring data, intended to support local regeneration activity. We're continuing this work.

questions.query: Describe your previous work or plans related to the Arbitrum ecosystem. How does your project strengthen Arbitrum's foundational infrastructure, improve developer efficiency, or accelerate the adoption of novel applications?
questions.explanation:
Astral builds open source tools + infrastructure for location-based dapps. This year, we:
- developed the Location Proof Protocol (built on EAS — deploying on Arbitrum mainnet very soon)
- built the Astral Logbook, a dapp for telling place-based stories using location proofs
- designing Spatial.sol, a Solidity library of geospatial data structures and algorithms, to make it easy for location-based builders
- developed resource guides, code examples and documentation to enhance the developer experience

This strengthens Arbitrum's foundational infrastructure through the introduction of new smart contract protocols, improves developer efficiency by offering open source, forkable solutions to hard engineering problems, and accelerates the adoption of novel applications by introducing primitives to serve a new vertical on Arbitrum.

questions.query: Would you like to share anything else about your project, team, or vision for the Arbitrum ecosystem that wasn't covered in the previous questions?
questions.explanation:
Astral was first conceived in the Genesis block of Kernel, a Web3 fellowship funded by Gitcoin at the time. It was founded by John X, a geospatial data scientist and Web3 builder who co-founded Toucan, co-chaired of the WEF’s Web3 Climate Action Working Group, worked at Ordnance Survey (the UK’s national mapping agency). John is a proven builder and leader at the intersection of Web3 and regenerative finance.

Since the project’s inception, we have aimed to be a intent, value oriented, and open source product, taking only grant and other public goods funding

We found our Head of Engineering, Ron E. after he and team won ETHDenver’s hackathon for ZK Maps, a project that provides location proofs using ZK technology. Ron is a passionate builder with a penchant for privacy and using blockchain to assist with solving the climate crisis. He led engineering teams at [ZED.RUN](http://ZED.RUN) and taught at Columbia University, with an extensive background in data imaging and computer vision.

Then came Danny. John and Danny met through Kernel. He serves as a contributor helping with growth and operations. Danny leads growth efforts at Sherlock, helping ensure the security of Web3 projects. Previously, he was management and strategy consultant with stints including McKinsey, PwC. He was a DeFi founder for an analytics solution, having won a hackathon via OnDeck fellowship’s hackathon.

Along our journey, we’ve:
    - Been founding members of the Climate Collective, a organization for climate-focused Web3 startups which now includes over 30 member organizations
    - Cofounded the Decentralized Geospatial Working Group with academic researchers from the EASIER Data Initiative
    - Served as Kolektivo’s project partner, developing GeoNFTs
    - Received Filecoin’s Development Grant for storing satellite imagery on IPFS using decentralized identifiers
    - Presented to the Open Geospatial Consortium
    - Won the Arweave Prize, Future of Blockchain 2020
    - Spoke at the European Space Agency's Living Planet Symposium 2022
    - Coordinated the forming of the GeoSpatial Decentralized Collaboration Group 2023
    - Served as Regeneration and DeFi guild(s) leads at KERNEL

Our project was selected to be part of the [GG20 Celo Public Goods Climate Bonus Round](https://mirror.xyz/celopg.eth/McicejfzasLM0nD5HKNdPukgQHvVrRVT2GiFwwzf8AA).

### **Celo Claim:**

Astral is actively developing a dApp to be deployed on the Celo Network

Astral builds open source decentralized geospatial tools to enable the development of 1,000 location-based onchain applications. To foster the growth of location-based applications, we are planning to introduce two pivotal features to the Celo ecosystem.

First, we plan to deploy our Location Proof Protocol EAS schema on Celo. This will allow developers to register location proofs and develop innovative proof strategies on Celo mainnet. We're particularly excited about building location proofs to support impact claims such as dMRV measurements.

Second, we are building the Astral Logbook, a client application running on our Location Proof Protocol. With the Logbook, people can **tell place-based stories** by registering log entries on Celo, visualizing entries on a map, and building collections based on groups, topics or areas.

These two initiatives are designed to enhance the Celo ecosystem by providing key infrastructure to build location-based applications, and an example of an open source dapp built on that infrastructure.

Astral has previously demonstrated its commitment to the Celo ecosystem through successful deployments, notably our GeoNFTs via Kolektivo project. The Kolektivo GeoNFT Registry module facilitated the minting, deployment, contract interactions, and listing of GeoNFTs (Geospatial Non-fungible Tokens) which are ERC-1155 tokens representing topological data of real-world areas. This initiative was one of the first to link real-world spaces with NFTs on Celo's Mainnet, emphasizing a climate focus.

Astral has no token or VC backing — we're purely public goods and grant funded. Receiving funding from Celo allows us to continue our deep and long-lasting relationship with Celo, further contributing to the ecosystem. 

Further Information:

GitHub Repositories:

General: https://github.com/AstralProtocol/astralprotocol

Kolektivo on Celo Mainnet: https://github.com/Kolektivo/geonft-registry-poc

Website: https://astral.global/

Presentation: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12ZfOGch8qZI1FKgiU1IRwn5R1J5GIFkShvGZaqDHzjU/edit?usp=sharing

This clear focus on innovative and climate-oriented applications underscores Astral’s role as a leader in the intersection of blockchain technology and environmental solutions.

questions.query: Provide a brief overview of your tool, library, or framework. What specific problem or inefficiency in the development process does it address?
questions.explanation:
Astral continues to develop open-source core tools, libraries, and frameworks to enable the decentralized geospatial web. Our mission is to provide tools that foster the development of 1000s of onchain location-based applications.

We’ve developed and launched Astral’s Location Proof Protocol, an open-source, extensible standard for creating and verifying user-controlled, cryptographically verifiable, and (optionally) private location proofs. Location proofs are a new primitive designed to enable developers to build location-based applications quickly.

We’ve also developed Astral’s Logbook, a consumer client application built on the Location Proof Protocol. The Logbook lets users register geotagged log entries onchain to share the spaces and places that matter.

We’re also conducting the necessary research and standards development for onchain GIS, developing the Spatial.sol, a collection of spatial data structures and geospatial algorithms built for the EVM.

We believe that Web3 developers are overlooking a significant category — location-based applications. We exist to help overcome a coordination failure regarding onchain location-based tooling, inhibiting the growth of this category of apps and infrastructure. Astral’s work directly addresses this by providing the core tooling, fostering a community of builders, researchers, and protocols, and establishing the necessary standards.

questions.query: How does your project reduce development barriers, improve efficiency, or enhance the security of Web3 projects? Please provide specific examples or metrics if available.
questions.explanation:
Spatial data structures and geospatial computation on decentralized systems are complex problems to solve. We’re working on producing secure, open-source tools that provide developers with a new Web3 primitive and dramatically reduce the complexity of building location-based apps.

First, we developed Astral’s Location Proof Protocol, which allows any protocol builder to create, verify, and visualize location proofs. We’ll continue to add ‘recipes’—our term for location proof strategies—to the Protocol and deploy it to EVM L2s and other chains.

Secondly, we continue serving as a hub for the onchain GIS researcher and developer community. Through this work, we’re focused on conducting necessary research around data architecture, GIS standards, and application development.

Lastly, we continue to develop core tooling that enables possible location-based protocol and application development. This includes developing the spatial data structures and GIS algorithms for EVM and continuing research into geospatial data storage and access technologies on IPFS. All of our solutions are open source and accompanied by developer documentation.

Astral has the following metrics:
- 5+ Consumer Applications Built (e.g., Logbook, Hyperware, ZKMaps, Kolectivo, etc.,)
- 3+ Protocols Building on Astral’s Location Proof Protocol
- 100+ Instances of Location Proof Protocol Usage
- 20+ Protocols, Projects, and Researchers participating in the Decentralized Geospatial Web Working Group
- 500 Github Commits
- 200+ Community Members across Telegram and Discord
- 1000k Social Media followers

questions.query: Provide a brief overview of your tool, library, or framework. What specific problem or inefficiency in the development process does it address?
questions.explanation:
The Astral Protocol provides open-source tools + infrastructure empowering developers to build user-centric, verifiable location-based apps on the decentralized web.

We create the tools, standards and protocols necessary for a decentralized geospatial web, simplifying how Web3 developers integrate spatial and location data into their apps.

There is no simple, dev-friendly way to work with user locations in Web3 software systems. So we developed the Location Proof Protocol to introduce a new Web3 primitive representing user locations.

The Location Proof Protocol is a framework for creating location proofs, which are digitally-signed proof of time and place. We’ve already launched our beta, including the LPP specification, reference implementation, API and SDK. The LPP is built on EAS — our v0.1 schema is deployed on multiple chains: Celo, Base, Arbitrum and Sepolia.

In addition to location proofs, we’re researching **verifiable geocomputation** systems — geospatial algorithms in smart contracts and cryptographic protocols. We’ve also been doing R+D on **p2p geospatial data systems** for efficiently storing, managing, and accessing diverse spatial data types, such as sensor measurements, drone imagery, and satellite data.

These tools unlock a new category of trustworthy, location-aware decentralized applications and robust geospatial workflows, enabling use cases like:

- Environmental monitoring and digital MRV
- Climate modeling and forecasting
- Transparent transport and mobility systems
- Interactive location-based games
- Compliance verification and fraud detection
- Secure human rights reporting

You can see more about how our tools will make the developer experience easier on the README of our (in development!) Typescript SDK: https://github.com/decentralizedGeo/astral-sdk/.

questions.query: How does your project reduce development barriers, improve efficiency, or enhance the security of Web3 projects? Please provide specific examples or metrics if available.
questions.explanation:
Astral’s mission is to enable the development of thousands of onchain applications which are location-based and / or use location data.

Our belief is that Web3 developers have overlooked a major app category — location-based apps — because of challenges in working with location data.

- Creating trustworthy location claims is tricky
- Geospatial algorithms are complicated
- Spatial data needs special storage and access systems

Our work is focused on solving these problems, and simplifying developer experience when it comes to building location-based dapps.

In July 2024, we launched the Astral Location Proof Protocol to enable builders to deploy location proofs. This application was built on Ethereum Attestation Service (EAS) and deployed to Celo, Base, Arbitrum, and Sepolia, with a few hundred location proofs registered onchain. We have one demo app — the Astral Logbook — and one community app — TOUCHGRASS.CLUB — deployed, and more in development.

We have a roadmap that includes research and development into verifiable geocomputation (Spatial.sol), p2p geospatial data management (ipfs-stac), privacy-preserving location proofs (zero knowledge location proofs, TEEs)

In January of this year, we deployed the Astral API, which serves as a unified gateway to the decentralized geospatial web. This provides a single endpoint across the chain and harmonized geospatial data while supporting advanced querying and serving as an SDK integration.

Other highlights include:

- Our first peer-reviewed paper was selected for publication — we’re presenting in in April 2025 (https://osf.io/bg2uq_v1)
- At the Funding the Commons x Earth Commons Hackathon (Q4 2024) we had over 10 hacker submissions (https://dorahacks.io/hackathon/ftc-2024/buidl, filter for Astral bounty)
- We were shortlisted at the EAS Fellowship Demo Day, Q2 2024
- We presented at Demo Day during Kernel’s Genesis Block
- We won the Arweave Prize at the Future of Blockchain hackathon in 2020
- We’ve gotten grants from the Filecoin Foundation, Climate Collective and Arbitrum / Thrive to support our R+D

We’re committed to building open source software, and have joined up with a team from the University of Maryland’s Geographical Sciences Department to co-maintain repositories focused on decentralized geospatial technology: [github.com/DecentralizedGeo](http://github.com/DecentralizedGeo)

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation:
Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.

In the upcoming months, we plan to:

- Publish the Astral SDK as an npm package, giving Typescript developers an easy way to create, publish, fetch and verify location proofs
- Build a block scanner-style UI — including map visualizations — to explore location proofs
- Support pilot ecosystem developers (could this be you? Reach out!)
- Present our first peer-reviewed paper at GISRUK 2025 in Bristol, UK
- Research the landscape of proof-of-location systems, share our findings
- Develop the first Location Proof Recipe Extensions
- Refine the beta Location Proof Protocol into a technical specification to share with the geospatial community via the Open Geospatial Consortium
- Submit for more extensive grant funding to support our open source ecosystem development
- R+D on a smart contract library for geometric and topological algorithms (Spatial.sol)
- Research privacy-preserving location proofs, including zero knowledge- and TEE-based methods

In addition to these initiatives, and funding raised will help pay for subscriptions, server and hosting costs.

We’ve bootstrapped this work to build public goods with the support of the Gitcoin community, and would love to continue making progress.

Describe your project in a few paragraphs (ideally including a problem statement, solution, roadmap, and timeline for implementation)
questions.explanation:
Problem Statement
Integrating precise and verifiable geospatial data within blockchain applications remains a significant challenge. Traditional geospatial services are often centralized, lacking transparency and complete user control, which limits their application in scientific and decentralized environments.

Solution:
Astral addresses these challenges by developing open-source tools and protocols enabling secure, verifiable, and decentralized sharing of geospatial data. Our solutions include:
 
Astral Location Proof Protocol: Enables applications to securely verify location data's authenticity.

Astral SDK: This gives developers the tools needed to integrate geospatial capabilities into their decentralized applications effortlessly.

Roadmap and Timeline for Implementation:

Q2 2025: Enhance the Astral SDK for broader developer adoption and integrate additional geospatial data verification protocols.

Q3 2025: Launch the next version of the Location Proof Protocol, which will include improved scalability and privacy features using zero-knowledge proofs.

Q4 2025: Deploy the updated protocols on mainnet and expand our partnerships with academic and research institutions to test and validate our tools in real-world scientific studies.

Q1 2026: Focus on community-driven development and conduct several hackathons and workshops to increase community engagement and feedback.

questions.query: How does your project support the mission or goals of DeSci?
questions.explanation:
Astral’s project supports and aligns with the mission of DeSci. Our focus is on conducting the necessary research, establishing standards, and building the core tooling necessary to foster decentralized geospatial discipline. We believe our work will enable geospatial data collection via geotagged measurements and verifiable climate modeling. Presently, we work directly with researchers at the University of Maryland and various NGOs as a chair for a Decentralized Geospatial Web Working Group (DGWWG).
Our commitment is to advance the geospatial disciplines and work with an array of builders, researchers, and developers who share our vision and mission.

questions.query: Describe how funds from the grants program will be used for your project.
questions.explanation: Grant funding will be allocated to our primary researcher and developer, allowing them to conduct research and open-source software development. Their focus is outlined in our roadmap. The impact of that work is to establish decentralized data science, collection, and applications and develop the necessary tooling to enable location-based applications.
